<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="1" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1941,2041]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="1" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,484,1941,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis of the new genus.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[493,644,1942,1968]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="1" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
with Ant. IV clearly subdivided (usually more than 15 subsegments), trochanteral spines present. Tunica present or absent, never filamentous, tenent-hairs acuminated. A pair of neosminthuroid chaetae, apex of mucro asymmetric, mucronal chaeta absent, anterior dens with 3:2:2:2:1:1:1 or more chaetae. Trichobothrial complex 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[517,576,152,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">ABC</emphasis>
forming an obtuse angle opening backwards and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1124,1163,152,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">AB</emphasis>
subequal to 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1302,1341,152,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">BC</emphasis>
. Female subanal appendages large and thick, pointing to anal opening. Mature males with a pair of strongly sclerotized, twisted, horn-like Ap and Ae chaetae on AOIII (
<figureCitation box="[694,784,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1918,1943]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,175,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1884]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. A, mature male Ant. III showing the twisted, horn-like Ap and Ae chaetae on AOIII; B, detail of AOIII sensilla (male); C, mature female AOIII chaetotaxy; D, detail of AOIII sensilla (female). Scale bar 10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628977/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), a pair of lateral horn-like cuticular spines in the clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[160,227,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1869,1894]" captionTargetBox="[388,1195,166,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[388,1198,166,1842]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. FIG 2. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. Head of a mature male, showing the cephalic chaetotaxy. Arrow pointing to clypeal lateral horn-like cuticular spines, arrow head pointing to smooth (degranulated) cuticular fields. Scale bar 20µm. FIG 3. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. mature male cephalic organ, arrows pointing to the vesicle next to the eye patch and the line of crenulated openings at the interocular area. Arrow head pointing to smooth (degranulated) areas. Scale bar 20µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628979/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and a special organ composed of a vesicle adjacent to the eye patch and a line of crenulated openings at the interocular area (
<figureCitation box="[341,410,297,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1869,1894]" captionTargetBox="[388,1195,166,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[388,1198,166,1842]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. FIG 2. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. Head of a mature male, showing the cephalic chaetotaxy. Arrow pointing to clypeal lateral horn-like cuticular spines, arrow head pointing to smooth (degranulated) cuticular fields. Scale bar 20µm. FIG 3. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. mature male cephalic organ, arrows pointing to the vesicle next to the eye patch and the line of crenulated openings at the interocular area. Arrow head pointing to smooth (degranulated) areas. Scale bar 20µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628979/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1417,332,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" box="[199,1417,332,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,363,333,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Etymology. K</emphasis>
erato (kἐρατο) is Greek for horn, in allusion to the male dimorphism on antennae and clypeus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,790,368,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Distribution and biogeographic considerations. C</emphasis>
ollections from State of 
<collectingRegion box="[1063,1113,369,395]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pará</collectingRegion>
(Carajás) Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1339,1407,369,395]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
in Amazon Forest south to Amazon river, State of 
<collectingRegion box="[692,832,405,431]" country="Brazil" name="Pernambuco" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pernambuco</collectingRegion>
(Goiana) Northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1099,1167,405,431]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
in Atlantic Forest close to the coast, and in the regions of the “Iron Quadrangle” and northern of 
<collectingRegion box="[990,1206,441,467]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Minas Gerais State</collectingRegion>
Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1436,441,467]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
in Cerrado Forest (
<figureCitation box="[368,459,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1098,1123]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,181,1073]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,174,1079]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution of the new genus in Brazil; A, general distribution; B, the putative barriers insulating the two new species; C, localities where the new genus was recorded in the State of Pará; D, localities where the new genus was recorded in the State of Minas Gerais. SFX, São Felix do Xingu; SB, Serra da Bocaina; CPC, Chapadão do Canga; FP, Ferro Puro; RF, Ramal Ferroviário; S11D, Serra Sul (Area D); PEA, single locality at Pernambuco; N1, N4, N5, plateaus at North mountain range." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628981" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628981/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
, C–D), found two related species which seem to be separated from each other by the Tocantins-Araguaia basin and São Francisco river (
<figureCitation box="[722,804,513,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1098,1123]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,181,1073]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,174,1079]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution of the new genus in Brazil; A, general distribution; B, the putative barriers insulating the two new species; C, localities where the new genus was recorded in the State of Pará; D, localities where the new genus was recorded in the State of Minas Gerais. SFX, São Felix do Xingu; SB, Serra da Bocaina; CPC, Chapadão do Canga; FP, Ferro Puro; RF, Ramal Ferroviário; S11D, Serra Sul (Area D); PEA, single locality at Pernambuco; N1, N4, N5, plateaus at North mountain range." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628981" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628981/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig 4B</figureCitation>
). Despite all the collections done so far, the genus seems to be missing from the areas north to the Amazon river.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,585,611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[323,525,585,611]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,525,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[532,638,585,611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[532,638,585,611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is easily separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sanchez-Garcia &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2016" box="[920,1071,585,611]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Songhaicinae">Songhaicinae</taxonomicName>
by means of the structure of the unguis and number of chaetae in the apical whorl of tibiotarsus (
<bibRefCitation author="Bernard, C. E. &amp; Wynne, J. J." box="[868,1141,621,647]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="77 - 90" refId="ref7905" refString="Bernard, C. E. &amp; Wynne, J. J. (2017) Disparrhopalites naasaveqw n. sp. from caves at Wupatki National Monument, Arizona, synonymy of Dietersminthurus Palacios-Vargas, Cuellar &amp; Vazquez, 1998 with Disparrhopalites Stach, 1956 and composition of Songhaicinae (Collembola: Sminthuridae). Zootaxa, 4319 (1), 77 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4319.1.4" type="journal article" year="2017">Bernard &amp; Wynne 2017</bibRefCitation>
), even the neosminthuroid chaetae, present in the new genus, is seen only in the genus 
<emphasis box="[835,953,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Songhaica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lasebikan, B. A. &amp; Betsch, J. M. &amp; Dallai, R." box="[961,1348,657,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="179 - 183" refId="ref8718" refString="Lasebikan, B. A., Betsch, J. M. &amp; Dallai, R. (1980) A new genus of Symphypleona (Collembola) from West Africa. Systematic Entomology, 5, 179 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1980. tb 00407. x" type="journal article" year="1980">Lasebikan, Betsch &amp; Dallai, 1980</bibRefCitation>
, among all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sanchez-Garcia &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2016" box="[186,341,693,719]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Songhaicinae">Songhaicinae</taxonomicName>
. The new genus combines characters from subfamilies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[953,1104,693,719]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
and Sphyrotecinae. The presence of a pair of Neosminthuroid chaetae, the asymmetrical mucronal tip, and the absence of the axial substitutions ams1 and as1 are features that occur in Sphyrotecinae (
<bibRefCitation author="Richards, W. R." box="[772,940,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 54" refId="ref9082" refString="Richards, W. R. (1968) Generic classification, evolution, and biogeography of the Sminthuridae of the world (Collembola). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 53, 1 - 54. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10053 fv" type="journal article" year="1968">Richards 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[953,1095,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 227" refId="ref7984" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1980) Elements pour une monographie des collemboles symphypleones (Hexapodes, Apterygotes). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A Zoologie, 116, 1 - 227." type="journal article" year="1980">Betsch 1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[1107,1166,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="13 - 18" refId="ref8024" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1997) An ontogenetically focused chaetotaxial scheme in Symphypleona (collembolan): the 6 th abdominal segment. Pedobiologia, 41, 13 - 18." type="journal article" year="1997">1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A." box="[1178,1431,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="5 - 12" refId="ref8059" refString="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A. (1994) Chaetotaxic nomenclature of the head, thorax and abdomen in Symphypleona (Insecta, Collembola). Acta Zoologica Fennica, 195, 5 - 12." type="journal article" year="1994">Betsch &amp; Waller 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bretfeld, G." box="[151,312,801,827]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 318" refId="ref8328" refString="Bretfeld, G. (1999) Symphypleona. In: Dunger W. (Ed.), Synopses on Palaearctic Collembola, Vol. 2. Abhandlungen und Berichte des Naturkundemuseum Gorlitz, 71 (1), 1 - 318." type="journal article" year="1999">Bretfeld 1999</bibRefCitation>
). The numerous anterior chaetae on dens, the long antennae with clearly multidivided Ant. IV and the presence of secondary ams2 and ams3 chaetae on Abd. VI are diagnostic for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[1053,1204,837,863]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[1218,1362,837,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 227" refId="ref7984" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1980) Elements pour une monographie des collemboles symphypleones (Hexapodes, Apterygotes). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A Zoologie, 116, 1 - 227." type="journal article" year="1980">Betsch 1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[1373,1432,837,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="13 - 18" refId="ref8024" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1997) An ontogenetically focused chaetotaxial scheme in Symphypleona (collembolan): the 6 th abdominal segment. Pedobiologia, 41, 13 - 18." type="journal article" year="1997">1997</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A." box="[151,404,873,899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="5 - 12" refId="ref8059" refString="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A. (1994) Chaetotaxic nomenclature of the head, thorax and abdomen in Symphypleona (Insecta, Collembola). Acta Zoologica Fennica, 195, 5 - 12." type="journal article" year="1994">Betsch &amp; Waller 1994</bibRefCitation>
), therefore, we redefined subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[809,960,873,899]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
to fit the new genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[199,401,909,935]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,401,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[406,509,909,935]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[406,509,909,935]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1963" box="[631,740,910,935]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Temeritas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[631,740,910,935]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Temeritas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority=", Novakatianna and Pararrhopalites" authorityName="Novakatianna and Pararrhopalites" box="[752,1270,909,935]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Caprainea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[752,872,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Caprainea</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[883,1040,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Novakatianna</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1090,1270,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pararrhopalites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
genera with trochanteral spines and no post-antennal chaetae or dorsal abdominal glands. These genera, but 
<emphasis box="[151,331,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pararrhopalites</emphasis>
, share the presence of 11 or more anterior chaetae on dens, and Ant. IV with at least 13 subsegments. The presence of long thick chaetae on Ant. III, even though in different number and distribution in each genus, is questionable as a diagnostic feature, as in the new genus those chaetae seems to be missing or found only in adult males as part of the AOIII, while females present only ordinary short chaetae in the antennae. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1963" box="[1327,1436,1090,1115]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Temeritas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1327,1436,1090,1115]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Temeritas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are several long and thick chaetae, either in basal and apical half of Ant. III. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Medeiros &amp; Bellini, 2019" authorityName="Medeiros &amp; Bellini" authorityYear="2019" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Temeritas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxalis">
<emphasis box="[1217,1381,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">T. paradoxalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Medeiros, G. S. &amp; Bellini, B. C." pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="536 - 552" refId="ref8833" refString="Medeiros, G. S. &amp; Bellini, B. C. (2019) Two new species of Temeritas Richards (Collembola, Symphypleona, Sminthuridae) from Neotropical Region, with comments on the genus. Zootaxa, 4586 (3), 536 - 552. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4586.3.9" type="journal article" year="2019">Medeiros &amp; Bellini, 2019</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Arle &amp; Oliveira, 1977" authorityName="Arle &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="1977" box="[462,863,1161,1187]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Temeritas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ormondae">
<emphasis box="[462,605,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">T. ormondae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Arle, R. &amp; Oliveira, M. M." box="[611,863,1161,1187]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref7860" refString="Arle, R. &amp; Oliveira, M. M. (1977) O genero Temeritas Delamare &amp; Massoud, 1963 na Amazonia (Collembla Symphypleona). Boletim do Museu Paraense Emilio Goeldi, New Series, 87, 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="1977">Arle &amp; Oliveira, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
present only short ordinary chaetae on Ant. III, as exceptions for the genus. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName box="[578,698,1197,1223]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" genus="Caprainea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[578,698,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Caprainea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presents 4–5 such chaetae placed only in the basal half, while in 
<emphasis box="[151,308,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Novakatianna</emphasis>
there are 4 chaetae on the basal and one in the apical third of Ant. III. None of those long thick chaetae are component of the AOIII (
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[475,619,1269,1295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 227" refId="ref7984" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1980) Elements pour une monographie des collemboles symphypleones (Hexapodes, Apterygotes). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A Zoologie, 116, 1 - 227." type="journal article" year="1980">Betsch 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nayrolles, P." box="[630,804,1269,1295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 94" refId="ref8959" refString="Nayrolles, P. (1991) La chetotaxie antennaire des collemboles symphypleones. Travaux du Laboratoire d'Ecobiologie des Arthropodes Edaphiques, Toulouse, 6 (3), 1 - 94." type="journal article" year="1991">Nayrolles 1991</bibRefCitation>
), instead, adult males of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[1123,1325,1269,1295]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1123,1325,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1332,1436,1269,1295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1332,1436,1269,1295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
present a single pair of thick, twisted, horn-like Ae and Ap on AOIII (
<figureCitation box="[915,1002,1305,1331]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1918,1943]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,175,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1884]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Keratosminthurus tapigu gen. nov. sp. nov. A, mature male Ant. III showing the twisted, horn-like Ap and Ae chaetae on AOIII; B, detail of AOIII sensilla (male); C, mature female AOIII chaetotaxy; D, detail of AOIII sensilla (female). Scale bar 10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3628977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3628977/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). The genus 
<emphasis box="[1142,1322,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pararrhopalites</emphasis>
also lacks long chaetae on Ant. III, but usually has less than 11 chaetae on anterior dens (often 3,2,1…1 or 3,2,2,1…1), and most Neotropical species present about 8–11 Ant. IV subsegments. Nevertheless, 
<emphasis box="[1084,1216,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">P. palaciosi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zeppelini, D. &amp; Brito, R. A." pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1733 - 1744" refId="ref9377" refString="Zeppelini, D. &amp; Brito, R. A. (2014) Two New Species of Pararrhopalites (Collembola: Symphypleona: Sminthuridae) in Brazil. Florida Entomologist, 97 (4), 1733 - 1744. https: // doi. org / 10.1653 / 024.097.0449" type="journal article" year="2014">Zeppelini &amp; Brito, 2014</bibRefCitation>
stands as an exception. This is the only species of 
<emphasis box="[795,975,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pararrhopalites</emphasis>
known to be epigean in the Neotropical region, with 8+8 eyes, Ant. IV 18-subsegmented, and anterior dens showing 3,2,2,2,2,1,1 chaetae, just like other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[151,306,1485,1511]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sminthurinae">Sminthurinae</taxonomicName>
. The genus differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[589,791,1485,1511]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[589,791,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[800,907,1485,1511]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[800,907,1485,1511]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by lacking the neosminthuroid chaeta and the sexual dimorphism.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
Many aspects of the chaetotaxy, Ant. IV subsegmentation (
<tableCitation box="[854,937,1557,1583]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="19.[151,239,1126,1150]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparison among related genera of Sminthurinae. (+) present, (-) absent.Ant. IV, number of Ant. IV subsegments. Ant. III, number of long thick chaetae on Ant. III (Ae-Ap, Apical Organ chaetae). Dens, number of anterior chaetae on dens. Nsmin, neosminthuroid chaeta. Body, macrochaetae on body. ♂, male sexual dimorphism. Sy, symmetric. Asy, asymmetric. (Exceptional condition in parenthesis)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/989210F7FFB55E322DB3FBCAFD17FB3B" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" tableUuid="989210F7FFB55E322DB3FBCAFD17FB3B">Table 1</tableCitation>
), antenna/body ratio, foot complex structure will differentiate those genera from 
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[559,761,1593,1619]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[559,761,1593,1619]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[769,875,1593,1619]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[769,875,1593,1619]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[936,1079,1593,1619]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 227" refId="ref7984" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1980) Elements pour une monographie des collemboles symphypleones (Hexapodes, Apterygotes). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A Zoologie, 116, 1 - 227." type="journal article" year="1980">Betsch 1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M." box="[1091,1150,1593,1619]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="13 - 18" refId="ref8024" refString="Betsch, J. - M. (1997) An ontogenetically focused chaetotaxial scheme in Symphypleona (collembolan): the 6 th abdominal segment. Pedobiologia, 41, 13 - 18." type="journal article" year="1997">1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bretfeld, G." box="[1162,1321,1593,1619]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 318" refId="ref8328" refString="Bretfeld, G. (1999) Symphypleona. In: Dunger W. (Ed.), Synopses on Palaearctic Collembola, Vol. 2. Abhandlungen und Berichte des Naturkundemuseum Gorlitz, 71 (1), 1 - 318." type="journal article" year="1999">Bretfeld 1999</bibRefCitation>
; Sánchez- García &amp; Engel 2016; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bernard, C. E. &amp; Wynne, J. J." box="[408,683,1629,1655]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="77 - 90" refId="ref7905" refString="Bernard, C. E. &amp; Wynne, J. J. (2017) Disparrhopalites naasaveqw n. sp. from caves at Wupatki National Monument, Arizona, synonymy of Dietersminthurus Palacios-Vargas, Cuellar &amp; Vazquez, 1998 with Disparrhopalites Stach, 1956 and composition of Songhaicinae (Collembola: Sminthuridae). Zootaxa, 4319 (1), 77 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4319.1.4" type="journal article" year="2017">Bernard &amp; Wynne 2017</bibRefCitation>
). The posterior cephalic chaetotaxy of the new genus is a point for discussion, 
<taxonomicName authority="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima, 2020" authorityName="Zeppelini &amp; Brito &amp; Zampaulo &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2020" box="[283,485,1665,1691]" class="Entognatha" family="Collembola" genus="Keratosminthurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,485,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Keratosminthurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[493,600,1665,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[493,600,1665,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
presents axial chaetae at rows 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[953,973,1664,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">A</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[988,1007,1665,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">B</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1022,1042,1664,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">C</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1099,1119,1665,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">D</emphasis>
as 5,3,3,5. The axial chaeta 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,170,1701,1727]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">B</emphasis>
is absent in all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[349,503,1701,1727]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sminthuridae</taxonomicName>
, it is normally seen in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Betsch &amp; Waller 1994)" baseAuthorityName="Betsch &amp; Waller" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[760,1201,1701,1727]" class="Entognatha" family="Arrhopalitidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Arrhopalitidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A." box="[939,1193,1701,1727]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="5 - 12" refId="ref8059" refString="Betsch, J. - M. &amp; Waller, A. (1994) Chaetotaxic nomenclature of the head, thorax and abdomen in Symphypleona (Insecta, Collembola). Acta Zoologica Fennica, 195, 5 - 12." type="journal article" year="1994">Betsch &amp; Waller 1994</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and some species of 
<emphasis box="[151,331,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Pararrhopalites</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[347,688,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">e.g. Pararrhopalites palaciosi</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[703,825,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">P. hennigii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Palacios-Vargas, J. G. &amp; Zeppelini, D." box="[841,1243,1736,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" pagination="21 - 37" refId="ref9044" refString="Palacios-Vargas, J. G. &amp; Zeppelini, D. (1995) Seven new Arrhopalites (Hexapoda: Collembola) from Brazilian and Mexican caves. Folia Entomologica Mexicana, 93, 21 - 37." type="journal article" year="1995">Palacios-Vargas &amp; Zeppelini, 1995</bibRefCitation>
), as exception in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[151,306,1773,1799]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sminthuridae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2015]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
Notwithstanding, the most striking features that differentiate the new genus from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[1242,1393,1809,1835]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sminthuridae</taxonomicName>
are those related to its sexual dimorphism. The females are mostly alike all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lubbock" authorityYear="1862" box="[953,1107,1845,1871]" class="Entognatha" family="Sminthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sminthuridae</taxonomicName>
, with a pair of large subannal appendages (mi5) pointing to anal opening. Males, at the other hand, present striking and unique sexual dimorphism, with modification in the Ap and Ae chaetae of the AOIII, a pair of horn-like spines in the clypeus and an unknown organ in the interocular area, supposed to be a sort of pheromone dispersant, as it is only present in males and has a glandular aspect.
</paragraph>
